@b-slim I think "injective" is fine here, a regex->match extraction can be thought of as a a function.

JavascriptExtractionFn also supports the injective property and it doesn't extend FunctionalExtraction.

A hypothetical  "injective" use case might be a dimension value with various formats that all contain some unique ID, where the regex is used to strip out parts of the dim val that don't provide any unique information beyond the ID substring.

@KurtYoung

> I think retVal should be sorted before return

I forgot to ask a question on this. Why it should be sorted? I think multi-vals dimension is an array not a set. For arrays, should {a, b} be different from {b, a} ?

:+1:

@drcrallen  havingSpec will just be null if user does not have it in the query, it is not mandatory.
the problem with default was that if user specified a "having" clause and made a mistake in type name, druid will silently use AlwaysHavingSpec which will produce incorrect result with no errors. this PR will fail the query if user made a typing mistake.
